public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String a = new String("hello");  // explicitly creates a new object
        String b = new String("hello");  // another new object
        String c = "hello";              // from string pool
        String d = "hello";              // same pool entry

        System.out.println(a == b);       // false — different objects
        System.out.println(a.equals(b));  // true  — same content
        System.out.println(c == d);       // true  — same pool object (implementation detail!)
        System.out.println(a.equals(c));  // true  — same content

        // Case-insensitive comparison:
        System.out.println("HELLO".equalsIgnoreCase("hello"));
    }
}

instruction:
Strings are immutable — `s = s + "more"` creates a new String object each time. In a loop this is slow and wasteful.

`StringBuilder` is mutable — `.append()` modifies it in place:

```java
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
sb.append("Hello");
sb.append(", World");
String result = sb.toString();
```

Build a comma-separated list using StringBuilder.

starter:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String[] fruits = {"Apple", "Banana", "Cherry", "Date"};

        // BAD way (creates many String objects):
        // String result = "";
        // for (String f : fruits) result += f + ", ";

        // GOOD way with StringBuilder:
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        for (int i = 0; i < fruits.length; i++) {
            sb.append(fruits[i]);
            if (i < fruits.length - 1) sb.append(", ");
        }
        System.out.println(sb.toString());
        System.out.println("Length: " + sb.length());
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder("Hello World");
        System.out.println(sb);

        sb.insert(5, ",");           // insert comma after Hello
        System.out.println(sb);

        sb.replace(7, 12, "Java");  // replace World with Java
        System.out.println(sb);

        sb.append("!");
        System.out.println(sb);

        System.out.println(new StringBuilder("racecar").reverse());
    }
}
